\begin_layout Standard
To clarify this idea, it is useful to clarify our notation to distinguish
 between the population parameters (numbers the describe the population)
 versus the sample statistics (numbers that describe the sample).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Population Parameters - These quantities will be denoted with Greek letters
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 for means, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 for proportions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 for variances.
 These are the quantities that we are interested in, but do not know the
 actual values (unless we perform a complete census on the population).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sample Statistics - These are the quantities that are calculated from the
 sample and will be denoted with Roman letters, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 for means, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for proportions, 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2}$
\end_inset

 for variances.
 We only care about these values in the sense that they are proxies for
 the population parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a sample to be representative of the population, we want it to be selected
 in a manner that avoid bias.
 For example, a political phone survey should avoid just calling retired
 (and generally more conservative) individuals but try to sample both young
 and old people in roughly the same percentage as in the population.
 If we are performing a study on 50-60 year old males with heart disease,
 we should strive to get an ethnic diversity that reflects the population,
 or recognize the sample is actually representative of a particular subpopulatio
n.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sampling distribution of a proportion 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to conclude the null hypothesis is incorrect, we must compare the
 data we observed to what we could have seen if the null hypothesis was
 correct.
 Just as Eratosthenes expected to see equal length shadows if the earth
 was flat, we need to consider what data we could have observed if the null
 hypothesis was correct.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To assess if the our data is consistent with the null hypothesis, it is
 useful to reduce the observed data into a summary statistic that is related
 to the hypothesis of interest.
 Sometimes the summary statistic is obvious, but sometimes not.
 We then will compare the observed sample statistic to the distribution
 of statistic values that we could have seen.
 We will call this distribution of possible sample statistics (assuming
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is true) the sampling distribution of the statistic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several different methods we'll use to produce the sampling distributi
on and are often specific to a particular to the design of the study but
 the goal of producing possible realizations of the statistic that are consisten
t with the null hypothesis and the study design will be a constant theme.
\end_layout

